UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2614
1 A RESOLUTION honoring the life and legacy of Reverend Alfred Daniel "A.D."
2 King.
3 WHEREAS, although Alfred Daniel King, called "A.D." by family and friends,
4 lived in the shadows of his famous brother, Martin Luther King, Jr., he was a devoted
5 minister, civil rights leader, and courageous advocate for justice whose work profoundly
6 impacted the Commonwealth of Kentucky and the United States; and
7 WHEREAS, Alfred Daniel Williams King was born on July 30, 1930, in Atlanta,
8 Georgia. A.D. was the third child of Alberta Williams King and Martin Luther King, Sr.
9 A.D. married on June 17, 1950, to Naomi Barber, with whom he had five children: Alfred
10 Daniel, Jr., Alveda, Vernon, Derek, and Darlene; and
11 WHEREAS, as a youth A.D. King strongly resisted his father’s ministerial urgings,
12 but he eventually began assisting his father at Ebenezer Baptist Church. In 1959, A.D.
13 graduated from Morehouse College, and that same year he left Ebenezer to become
14 pastor of Mount Vernon First Baptist Church in Newnan, Georgia; and
15 WHEREAS, A.D. King was a participant in the African American freedom
16 struggle, often appearing at his brother’s side in movements in Atlanta and Birmingham
17 during the fight for civil rights. A.D. King was arrested with his brother Martin Luther
18 King, Jr., and 70 others while participating in an October 1960 lunch counter sit-in in
19 Atlanta; and
20 WHEREAS, in 1963, A.D. King became a leader of the Birmingham Campaign
21 while pastoring at First Street Baptist Church in nearby Ensley, Alabama. On May 11,
22 1963, A.D. King’s house was bombed. In August of that year, after a bomb exploded at
23 the home of a prominent black lawyer in downtown Birmingham, thousands of outraged
24 citizens poured into the city streets intent on revenge; and
25 WHEREAS, as rocks were thrown at gathering policemen and the situation
26 escalated, A.D. King climbed on top of a parked car and shouted to the rioters in an
27 attempt to quell their fury, "My friends, we have had enough problems tonight. If you’re
Page 1 of 3
