UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2614
1 going to kill someone, then kill me....Stand up for your rights, but with nonviolence"; and
2 WHEREAS, in 1965, A.D. King moved to Louisville, Kentucky, where he became
3 pastor at Zion Baptist Church (1965-1968). It became the largest African American
4 Baptist church in Kentucky. A.D. King also founded the Kentucky Christian Leadership
5 Council and assisted in the organization of the Committee for Open Housing's nightly
6 marches in Louisville; and
7 WHEREAS, on August 26, 1968, A.D. King's side office at Zion Baptist Church in
8 Louisville, Kentucky, was bombed; and
9 WHEREAS, like his brother, A.D. King was a staunch believer in the importance of
10 maintaining nonviolence in direct action campaigns. However, unlike his brother, A.D.
11 was able to remain mostly outside of the media spotlight. As one of his associates said,
12 "Not being in the limelight never seemed to affect him but because he stayed in the
13 background, many people never knew that he was deeply involved, too"; and
14 WHEREAS, after the assassination of his brother Martin Luther King, Jr., in April
15 1968, there was speculation that A.D. might become president of the Southern Christian
16 Leadership Conference (SCLC). A.D., however, made no effort to assume his brother’s
17 role, although he did continue to be active in the Poor People’s Campaign and in other
18 work on behalf of SCLC. Following the death of Martin Luther King, Jr., A.D. King
19 returned to Ebenezer Baptist Church and, in September 1968, was installed as co-pastor;
20 and
21 WHEREAS, praised by his father as "an able preacher, a concerned, loving pastor,"
22 A.D. King’s life was tragically cut short when he drowned on July 21, 1969, at the age of
23 38. As he was a strong swimmer, the family had suspicion around his untimely drowning
24 though no other cause of death was investigated; and
25 WHEREAS, A.D. King gave inspiration to many through his high ideals, morals,
26 and deep concern for his fellow citizens, and the devotion, patience, and understanding he
27 demonstrated to his family and friends were admired by others; and
Page 2 of 3
XXXX 3/30/2026 4:04 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 2614
1 WHEREAS, A.D. King was a person of magnanimous strengths with an
2 unimpeachable reputation for integrity, intelligence, fairness, and kindness, and by the
3 example he made of his life, he made this world a better place in which to live; and
4 WHEREAS, a compassionate and generous man, Reverend Alfred Daniel "A.D."
5 King continues to be missed by all who had the great fortune of knowing him;
6 NOW, THEREFORE,
7 Be it resolved by the Senate of the General Assembly of the Commonwealth of
8 Kentucky:
9 Section 1. The members of the Senate hereby honor the life and legacy of
10 Reverend Alfred Daniel "A.D." King.
11 Section 2. When the Senate adjourns this day, it does so in honor and memory
12 of Reverend Alfred Daniel "A.D." King.
13 Section 3. The Clerk of the Senate is directed to transmit a copy of this
14 Resolution to Senator Lindsey Tichenor for presentation.
